'''Matter''' is a [[technical standard]] for [[Home automation|smart home]] and [[Internet of things]] (IoT) devices.<ref>{{Cite web |title=What Is Matter? The New Smart Home Standard, Explained |url=https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/matter-explained |access-date=17 March 2023 |website=PCMag |language=en}}</ref><ref name="kas19" /><ref name="pur22" /> It aims to improve [[interoperability]] and compatibility between different manufacturers and security, and always allowing local control as an option.<ref name="zdnetjoseph2020">{{Cite web |title=With Amazon, Apple and Google onboard, this new alliance aims to make your smart home work properly |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/with-amazon-apple-and-google-onboard-this-new-alliance-aims-to-make-your-smart-home-work-properly/ |access-date=17 March 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Christine |title=Matter's Internet of Things standard, certification ready for developers |url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/10/04/matters-internet-of-things-standard |website=TechCrunch |access-date=17 March 2023 |date=4 October 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Seifert |first1=Dan |title=Amazon, Apple, and Google's smart home partnership is close |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/4/16/22387252/project-chip-will-finally-ship-later-this-year |website=The Verge |access-date=17 March 2023 |date=16 April 2021}}</ref>

Matter originated in December 2019 as the Project Connected Home over IP (CHIP) working group, founded by [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Google]], and the [[Connectivity Standards Alliance]] (when it was the Zigbee Alliance).<ref name="kas19" /><ref name="zdnetjoseph2020" /> Subsequent members include [[IKEA]], [[Huawei]], Heiman<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-01 |title=Shenzhen Heiman Technology Co. Ltd. |url=https://csa-iot.org/member/shenzhen-heiman-technology-co-ltd/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref>, and [[Schneider Electric|Schneider]].<ref name="mih" /><ref name="mis20" /> Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 4 October 2022.<ref name="gh22" /><ref name="csa22" /><ref name="tv22" /> The Matter [[software development kit]] is [[Open-source software|open-source]] under the [[Apache License]].<ref name="chi21" />

A [[software development kit]] (SDK) is provided [[royalty-free]],<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Hill |first=Simon |date=3 April 2022 |title=What's the Matter? We Explain the New Smart Home Standard |url=https://www.wired.com/story/what-is-matter/ |access-date=30 April 2022 |magazine=Wired |publisher=Condé Nast}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=project-chip/connectedhomeip |date=25 June 2024 |url=https://github.com/project-chip/connectedhomeip |access-date=25 June 2024 |publisher=Connectivity Standards Alliance}}</ref> though the ability to commission a finished product into a Matter network in the field mandates certification and membership fees,<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Device Attestation - latest - Silicon Labs Matter Silicon Labs |url=https://docs.silabs.com/matter/latest/matter-device-attestation/ |access-date=26 June 2024 |website=docs.silabs.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Certification Process {{!}} Why Certify {{!}} |url=https://csa-iot.org/certification/why-certify/ |access-date=26 June 2024 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref> entailing both one-time, recurring, and per-product costs.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Become a Member {{!}} The Future of IOT |url=https://csa-iot.org/become-member/ |access-date=26 June 2024 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref> This is enforced using a [[public key infrastructure]] (PKI) and so-called device attestation certificates.<ref name=":1" />

Matter-compatible software updates for many existing hubs became available in late 2022,<ref name="msh22" /><ref name="goog22" /><ref name="tv22am" /> with Matter-enabled devices and [[software updates]] starting to release in 2023.<ref name="cnet22" />

The primary goal of Matter is to improve interoperability for the current smart home ecosystem. CSA and its members aim for the Matter logo to become ubiquitous and for consumers to instantly recognise it as a smart home device that will "just work".<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Matter: Making the smart home a more connected, comfortable, and helpful place |author=Connectivity Standards Alliance |author-link=Connectivity Standards Alliance |date=3 November 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oHsnjZPuqKM |access-date=22 April 2024 |via=YouTube}}</ref> However, Matter logos do not imply that devices will "just work"; infrastructure is also still required for full functionality, like a Wi-Fi network (which may need to be dual-band) and a Matter controller, and often, an app for each kind of device.<!-- Not sure how to specify - could list - Apple HomePod or Apple TV for Apple Home, a Google Nest Hub for Google Home, a SmartThings hub for Samsung, an Amazon device for Alexa, etc, or could say recent vintage smart speaker or other smart, recent-vintage, microphone-equipped device supporing Matter.  --> 

== Background ==
In December 2019, Amazon, Apple, Google, Samsung [[SmartThings]] and the [[Zigbee]] Alliance announced the collaboration and formation of the working group of Project Connected Home over IP. The goal of the project is to simplify development for smart home product brands and manufacturers while increasing the compatibility of the products for consumers.<ref name="guvy19" /><ref name="has19" />

The standard operates on [[Internet Protocol]] (IP) and functions via one or more controllers that connect and manage devices within a local network, eliminating the need for multiple proprietary hubs for each ecosystem. Matter-certified products are engineered to operate locally and do not depend on an internet connection for their core functions.<ref>{{Cite web |title=What is Matter? |url=https://developers.home.google.com/matter/overview |access-date=22 April 2024 |website=Google Home Developers |language=en}}</ref> Leveraging [[IPv6 address]]ing,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Thread and IPv6 {{!}} Matter |url=https://developers.home.google.com/matter/primer/thread-and-ipv6 |access-date=22 April 2024 |website=Google Home Developers |language=en}}</ref> the standard facilitates seamless communication with cloud services. Its goal is to facilitate interoperability among smart home devices, mobile apps, and cloud services, employing a specific suite of IP-based networking technologies such as [[Multicast DNS|mDNS]] and [[IPv6]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://csa-iot.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Matter-1.2-Core-Specification.pdf|title=Matter Specification - Version 1.2|date=18 October 2023|publisher=Connectivity Standards Alliance}}</ref> By adhering to a network design that operates at the [[Application layer|Application Layer]] of the [[OSI model|OSI 7 layer model]], Matter differs from protocols like Zigbee or [[Z-Wave]] and theoretically can function on any IPv6-enabled network. Presently, official support is limited to [[Wi-Fi]], [[Ethernet]], and the wireless mesh network [[Thread (network protocol)|Thread]].<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sGPRIkqWh3g |title=Matter Network Transport - Connectivity Standards Alliance |language=en |access-date=22 April 2024 |via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>

== Versions ==
Updates to the standard are planned to occur biannually.<ref name=":0" />
* Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 4 October 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Newsroom {{!}} Articles & Blogs {{!}} IOT |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/ |access-date=19 November 2022 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref> It introduced support for lighting products (such as [[mains power plugs]], [[electric light]]s and [[switch]]es), [[Door security|door lock]]s, [[thermostat]]s and [[heating, ventilation, and air conditioning]] controllers, blinds and shades, home security sensors (such as door, window and [[motion sensors]]), and televisions and streaming video players.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Matter Smart Home Standard Is Finally Available: Here's What It Means for Your Home |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/smart-home/matter-smart-home-standard-faq-a9475777045/ |access-date=19 November 2022 |website=Consumer Reports |date=3 November 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref>
* Version 1.1 of the specification was published on 18 May 2023. Although a new version, it did not include any new categories, only bug fixes and enhancements to existing SDK, API and devices.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 May 2023 |title=Matter 1.1 release — Enhancements for developers and devices |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/matter-1-1-release-enhancements-for-developers-and-devices/ |access-date=14 September 2023 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref>
* Version 1.2 of the specification was published on 23 October 2023. This version added nine new device types (refrigerators, portable air conditioners, dishwashers, laundry washers, [[robotic vacuum cleaner]]s, smoke and carbon monoxide alarms, air quality sensors, air purifiers, and fans). It also provides revisions and additions to existing categories, improvements to the specification and SDK, and certification and testing tools.<ref>{{cite web |title=Matter 1.2 Arrives with Nine New Device Types & Improvements Across the Board |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/matter-1-2-arrives-with-nine-new-device-types-improvements-across-the-board/ |website=Connectivity Standards Alliance |date=23 October 2023 |access-date=5 November 2023 }}</ref>
* Version 1.3 of the specification was published on 8 May 2024. This version added support for water and energy management devices as well as appliance support for ovens, microwave ovens, cooktops, extractor hoods, laundry dryers, and Matter-casting media players. Scenes and command-batching were also added.<ref>{{cite web |title=Matter 1.3 Specification announced |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/matter-1-3-specification-released/|website=Connectivity Standards Alliance |date=8 May 2024 |access-date=16 May 2024 }}</ref>
* Version 1.4 of the specification was released on 7 November 2024, introducing an expanded focus on electricity-related areas, including batteries, solar systems, home routers, water heaters, and heat pumps. It also featured enhancements to existing areas, such as increased support for electric vehicle chargers, along with significant improvements to Thread devices.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gomes |first=Vitor |date=7 November 2024 |title=Matter 1.4 chega com suporte a Energia Solar e promessas de economia de energia elétrica. |url=https://www.pontobyte.com/matter-1-4-anunciado-pela-csa/ |access-date=22 December 2024 |website=PontoBYTE |language=pt-BR}}</ref>
* Version 1.4.1 of the specification was released on 7 May 2025. This minor version adds NFC onboarding and multi-device setup.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Smarter Start: Matter 1.4.1 Makes Setup Easier |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/a-smarter-start-matter-1-4-1-makes-setup-easier/|website=Connectivity Standards Alliance |date=7 May 2025 |access-date=7 May 2025 }}</ref>
* Version 1.4.2 of the specification was released on 11 August 2025. The minor update made security enhancements to Matter networks and standardized various existing behaviors to improve networking. The update also made some changes to device support requirements for routers and other "network infrastructure managers," requiring them to be certified for Thread 1.4 and support addressing at least 150 devices.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 August 2025 |title=Matter 1.4.2 {{!}} Enhancing Security and Scalability for Smart Homes |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/matter-1-4-2-enhancing-security-and-scalability-for-smart-homes/ |access-date=30 August 2025 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref>
* Version 1.5 of the specification was published on 20 November 2025. This major update adds support for [[camera]]s, [[soil moisture sensor]]s and [[Energy management system (building management)|energy management]] features. Additionally, this version enhances the Closures service, allowing for modular motion types (e.g. sliding, rotating and opening) which can be leveraged by component builders to improve services such blinds, curtains, gates and doors.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-20 |title=Matter 1.5 Introduces Cameras, Closures, and Enhanced Energy Management Capabilities |url=https://csa-iot.org/newsroom/matter-1-5-introduces-cameras-closures-and-enhanced-energy-management-capabilities/ |access-date=2025-12-08 |website=CSA-IOT |language=en-US}}</ref>

For future versions, the working group has been working on support for ambient motion and presence sensing, environmental sensing and controls, closure sensors, [[energy management]], Wi-Fi access points, cameras, and [[major appliance]]s.<ref name=":0">{{Citation |title=Matter, the new Global Standard for the Smart Home, Debuts at the Amsterdam Launch Event | date=3 November 2022 |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=eFgG8isgMUc&t=15m34s |language=en |access-date=19 November 2022}}</ref>

== Supported devices ==
CSA maintains the official list of Matter-certified products,<ref name="csaps" /> and restricts use of the Matter logo to certified devices. Matter product certification is also stored on the CSA's Distributed Compliance Ledger (DCL),<ref>{{Cite web |title=Distributed Compliance Ledger |url=https://webui.dcl.csa-iot.org/ |access-date=22 April 2024 |website=webui.dcl.csa-iot.org}}</ref> which publishes attestation information about certified devices.

